PART II: UNCERTAINTY IN MEMORY
</strong></font></td></tr>

<tr>
<td align=center><em>Week</em></td>
<td align=center><em>Date</em></td> 
<td align=center><em>Ch.</em></td> 
<td  align=center><em>Topic</em> 
</td>
<td  align=center><em>Due or Assigned</em></td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td rowspan=2 align=center>5</td>
<td align=center>Tu 28 Sept</td> 
<td align=center>4</td> 
<td colspan=2>
Short-Term Memory (STM): Duration; Forgetting as interference
vs. decay; Capacity and chunking.  
STM capacity in novices and experts.
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align=center>Th 30 Sept</td> 
<td align=center>4-5</td> 
<td colspan=2>
<a href="shanks_expertise.html">
Expertise might be only practice.</a>  Scanning of STM: data and models.
Acoustic-semantic distinction in STM vs. LTM: independent manipulation
of primacy and recency effects.
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td rowspan=2 align=center>6</td>
<td align=center>Tu 5 Oct</td> 
<td align=center>5</td> 
<td colspan=2>
Acoustic-semantic distinction in STM vs. LTM: release from proactive
inhibition.  (If time: Brain substrates of memory. Amnesia, Indirect
tests of memory.)  Levels of processing. Encoding specificity.
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align=center>Th 7 Oct</td> 
<td align=center>6</td> 
<td colspan=2>
Eye-witness memory, with video demo.
Encoding specificity and state dependency.
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td rowspan=2 align=center>7</td>
<td align=center>Tu 12 Oct</td> 
<td align=center>6-7</td> 
<td>
<a href="threethemes.html">Three themes of memory</a>: actively
encoded; bound with context; actively reconstructed.  Memory
repression, reconstruction, and confabulation.  Imagery in memory:
Huge capacity; imagery and the mnemonist; imagery and advertising.
</td>
<td>
<a href="hw2intro.html">Homework 2 (blocking in associative learning)</a> 
DUE at beginning of class.
(<a href="hw2results.html">Summary of Data from Homework 2</a>.)
</td>
<tr>
<td align=center>Th 14 Oct</td> 
<td align=center>7</td> 
<td>
Discussion of proposals.  Imagery and memory: Context bound imagery;
Reality monitoring.  <a href="mazemodels.html">Imagistic vs. symbolic
representation.</a> <a
href="http://www.indiana.edu/~kruschke/prop_rep_abstract.html">Maze
running demo</a>.  Parallel processing of images vs. serial processing
of symbols.
</td>
<td><a href="relevance.html#proposal">Relevance paper PROPOSAL</a> 2 
DUE at beginning of class.</td></tr>

<tr>
<td rowspan=2 align=center>8</td>
<td align=center>Tu 19 Oct</td> 
<td align=center>7</td> 
<td>
Properties of imagery: rotation, scanning, distortions.
Imagery and perception: similarities in behavior; interference; neural
substrates.  
</td>
<td><a href="relevance.html#structure">Relevance PAPER</a> 2 DUE 
at beginning of class.</td></tr>
<tr>
<td align=center>Th 21 Oct</td> 
<td align=center>4-7</td> 
<td valign=center align=center>
